properties.Title: High Water Advisory Alert Issued For The Interlake
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for parts of the Interlake region due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up to date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-19T12:30:00-05:00

Area: Interlake region of Manitoba

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system tracking out of the northern Prairie provinces has spread wet snow mixed at times with rain into Whale Cove, Rankin Inlet, and Chesterfield Inlet today. Accumulations will likely be in the 2 to 4 cm range and will be limited somewhat by melting and compaction. The snow also continues in Naujaat today, and will continue to be heavier through today, tonight and even into Sunday. The snow may start to mix with rain overnight or on Sunday after which time further accumulations will be limited. Total snowfall accumulations at Naujaat this weekend will likely end up in the 20 to 30 cm range. In addition to the snow, strong southeast winds will gust to 60 or 70 km/h, creating blowing snow at times. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-20T00:44:30-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-19T08:45:30-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0378846475.2019
Area: Naujaat
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions tonight and Saturday. The winds will gradually ease on Saturday night. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-19T16:34:02-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-19T00:35:02-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2013067675.2019
Area: Dempster

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 30 cm is expected. Heavy snow will continue falling over higher elevations of Highway 3 tonight and is expected to ease near midday. Near 10 cm of snow has been reported at Kootenay Pass as of 1 a.m. MST, with an additional 10 to 20 cm possible. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of significant coastal rain and high-elevation snow is expected. Total rainfall: 60 to 90 mm near Natuashish and 45 to 60 mm near Nain. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm inland and over higher terrain. Timespan: continuing until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rain, at times heavy, is expected along the north coast of Labrador through Sunday. Over the higher elevations inland, precipitation will fall as heavy accumulating snow until midday today before changing to a mixture of rain and wet snow. Precipitation will taper to showers by Sunday evening over all areas. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Be prepared for possible winter conditions at higher elevations. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-19T23:43:42-00:00
